ong different policy actors; the relationships between democracy in education and in policy formation; and the hidden role of privatization.Based on interviews with key policy actors, including ministry bureaucrats, curriculum policy writers, stakeholder consultation participants, and political staffers, Curriculum Reform in Ontario provides a critique of conventional policy formulation processes. Pinto also suggests possibilities for more participatory approaches to policy formulation that can better support the critical role played by schools in creating democratic societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCurriculum changezOntario. 0aCurriculum planningzOntariovCase studies. 0aEducation and statezOntariovCase studies. 0aEducation, SecondaryxCurriculazOntarioxPlanningvCase studies. 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266155440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442661554423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442661554.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK